It would help if you&#39;d tell us what the problem is instead of presenting
your solution of the problem as the problem.

I&#39;ve never needed mocks inside of mocks - it doesn&#39;t even make sense.



On 5/9/02 4:18 PM, &quot;cilqproj&quot; &lt;cilqproj@...&gt; wrote:

&gt; First, some background:
&gt; 
&gt; I&#39;m fairly new to unit testing, but I&#39;m very much interested in it.
&gt; I&#39;ve begun to understand the basics of it, but I&#39;m about to start
&gt; implementing for a class that is far and above more complex than the
&gt; simple tutorial classes that I&#39;ve used for training purposes.
&gt; 
&gt; Now, my issues:
&gt; 
&gt; Assume I have a  Servlet has a service() method being called. Assume
&gt; also that I can&#39;t replicate the servlet environment  so I&#39;m using Mock
&gt; Objects ( http://mockobjects.sourceforge.net ) to keep the testing
&gt; light. 
&gt; 
&gt; If my service() method looks like this:
&gt; 
&gt; service() {
&gt; 
&gt; doSomething()
&gt; doAnotherThing()
&gt; doSomethingElse()
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; each of which require the setting of a significantly different state (
&gt; or MockObjects inside MockObjects, which I&#39;ve read breaks the
&gt; fundamental philosophy of unit testing and mock objects )
&gt; 
&gt; would it suffice to test doSomething(), doAnotherThing(),
&gt; doSomethingElse() or would good practice dictate that I test service()
&gt; since that&#39;s the method that will be involved in the integration of my
&gt; code with the rest of the system?
&gt; 
&gt; I guess my underlying questions are:
&gt; 
&gt; What are some guidelines for a &quot;unit&quot; ?
&gt; Is the assumption of tested units enough to warrant passing on the
&gt; composite methods that call those units?
&gt; 
&gt; Thanks for any help,
&gt; 
